We talked a few weeks ago about the documentary-filmmaker son of a financia=
l-services billionaire who hated working in financial services and loves al=
ternative medicine=C2=A0and =E2=80=9Carchetypal astrology.=E2=80=9D He now =
works as the head of environmental, social and governance affairs at his da=
d=E2=80=99s firm, Interactive Brokers Group Inc.  I wrote:Imagine being the=
=C2=A0deputy=C2=A0director of ESG at Interactive Brokers. Presumably you go=
t hired based on your background doing ESG initiatives at major financial f=
irms.=C2=A0Presumably you think of ESG as a real career path in finance, an=
d you have spent your career building expertise in the theory and practice =
and complex accounting of ESG.=C2=A0But you=E2=80=99ve got to compete with =
financial-services heirs, and=C2=A0British-monarchy heirs=C2=A0for that mat=
ter. ESG is, somewhat paradoxically, an attractive area of finance for peop=
le who don=E2=80=99t care about finance but do like the money it provides.B=
roadly speaking you might expect there to be a=C2=A0lot of those people. No=
t so much ESG heirs, maybe,=C2=A0but people who don=E2=80=99t care much abo=
ut finance and nonetheless want a job in financial services. You might assu=
me that there are a lot of people who go to fancy colleges and have a vague=
 desire to make the world a better place. As they approach graduation, they=
 go to the career-services office and say =E2=80=9Chow can I save the world=
?=E2=80=9D Career services says: =E2=80=9CWell, you can go work at a nonpro=
fit for a low salary, or you can go do environmental reporting=C2=A0at a bi=
g asset manager for a high salary.=E2=80=9D (Or, they go to their parents, =
who work in finance, and say =E2=80=9CI am going to save the world by worki=
ng at a nonprofit,=E2=80=9D and the parents say =E2=80=9Cwell let=E2=80=99s=
 not be too hasty, have you considered ESG investing? I could hook you up.=
=E2=80=9D) And so there is a steady supply of people who don=E2=80=99t care=
 about finance but who end up working in financial services=C2=A0in ESG rol=
es.If this is your model, you might expect:=09The ESG people will get paid=
=C2=A0less than the regular finance people at their firms, because there is=
 a glut of them and their alternative is working at nonprofits for much les=
s money; and=C2=A0=09There will be a certain amount of bad blood and suspic=
ion between the ESG people (who hate finance and want to save the world) an=
d the regular finance people (who like finance and, uh, sometimes get stere=
otyped as not caring so much about the world?).Here is a funny=C2=A0Financi=
al Times article about the booming market for ESG specialists, which sugges=
ts that that model is basically correct, but that=C2=A0it is changing as ES=
G investing becomes hugely popular and it is hard to fill roles:In a CFA In=
stitute analysis of 10,000 investment jobs advertised on LinkedIn, 6 per ce=
nt required sustainability skills, yet less than 1 per cent of the 1m inves=
tment professional profiles included in the study listed these skills on th=
eir profiles. ...As a consequence, pay gaps between ESG staff and other inv=
estment roles are closing fast. =E2=80=9C[Hiring] used to be cheaper becaus=
e sustainability was popular and everyone wanted to do it,=E2=80=9D Ferguso=
n said.Candidates are often fielding multiple offers that can be significan=
tly above their current salary. Ruck Keene said that for recruiters: =E2=80=
=9CIt=E2=80=99s quite difficult to get people over the line. Nobody wants t=
o lose their ESG specialist. We=E2=80=99re seeing compensation increases of=
 30 to 50 per cent.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6Education is another key factor. Thou=
gh the CFA Institute started offering a certificate in ESG investing last y=
ear, few business schools currently have programmes that offer both financi=
al and sustainability training to the same level. It=E2=80=99s still =E2=80=
=9Cpretty church and state=E2=80=9D, said Robert Eccles, an expert on susta=
inability reporting and strategies at the University of Oxford. =E2=80=9CFi=
nance people think it=E2=80=99s all BS, sustainability people don=E2=80=99t=
 know finance.=E2=80=9DI think that one way to understand the proliferation=
 of ESG reporting regimes, carbon credit trading systems, etc., is that add=
ing a lot of rules and complexity to ESG=C2=A0makes it feel more like finan=
ce. Lots of people in financial services are not all that interested in, sa=
y, tax policy, but if you give them 1,000 pages of tax regulations they wil=
l be like =E2=80=9Coh goody let=E2=80=99s find some trades!=E2=80=9DOr you =
could think of the 2008 financial crisis as being driven, to some extent, b=
y people asking themselves =E2=80=9Cwhat is the riskiest possible thing tha=
t I could construct that will nonetheless get a AAA rating from the credit =
ratings agencies?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CBuy things that yield a lot but are saf=
e=E2=80=9D is a reasonable, dull mandate for an investment manager, but =E2=
=80=9Cunderstand the ratings agency criteria for structured credit inside a=
nd out so that you can maximize yield subject to the constraint of achievin=
g a AAA rating=E2=80=9D is a fun puzzle.Similarly, if you take a stereotypi=
cal=C2=A0hedge fund manager and tell her =E2=80=9Ctry to make money but als=
o do good with your investments,=E2=80=9D she will find that first mandate =
clear and exciting, and the second one vague and open-ended. But if you tel=
l her =E2=80=9Ctry to make money and here is a thicket of regulations about=
 ESG reporting,=E2=80=9D she will say =E2=80=9Coh goody let=E2=80=99s find =
an arbitrage!=E2=80=9D What is the  most complicated way to own oil compani=
es and have a zero-carbon portfolio? If there are complex regulations to op=
timize, it just feels like a real finance job in a way that =E2=80=9Cmake t=
he world better=E2=80=9D does not. Elsewhere:Companies will need to reveal =
detailed information about their greenhouse gas pollution under a new U.S. =
Securities and Exchange Commission plan, marking a major shift in how corpo=
rations must show they are dealing with climate change.=C2=A0For the first =
time ever, the agency plans to require businesses to outline the risks a wa=
rming planet poses to their operations when they file registration statemen=
ts, annual reports or other documents. Some large companies will have to pr=
ovide information on emissions they don=E2=80=99t make themselves, but come=
 from other firms in their supply chain. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9COver the generat=
ions, the SEC has stepped in when there=E2=80=99s significant need for the =
disclosure of information relevant to investors=E2=80=99 decisions,=E2=80=
=9D SEC Chair Gary Gensler said in a statement. =E2=80=9CToday=E2=80=99s pr=
