<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Block trade whale</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditionally, if you own a huge amoun=
t of a stock or a bond, and you want to sell it, you call up an investment =
bank and ask it for a bid. You could, in theory, call someone else. You cou=
ld call BlackRock Inc., or some other big asset manager that owns lots of s=
tocks and bonds, and see if they want to buy. But you normally call an inve=
stment bank, for roughly three reasons:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: de=
cimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">You have the bank=E2=80=99s phone number. The bank is in the business=
 of covering you. Some salesperson at the bank talks to you frequently, tak=
es you out to dinner and says =E2=80=9Cif you ever need anything, call me.=
=E2=80=9D The bank is in the=C2=A0<em>business=C2=A0</em>of trading with yo=
u, which is not generally true of asset managers. If you call the bank and =
say =E2=80=9CI need you to buy a ton of this stock,=E2=80=9D the bank will =
try very hard to say yes, and feel like it has failed if it says no. If you=
 call BlackRock and say =E2=80=9CI need you to buy a ton of this stock,=E2=
=80=9D BlackRock will say yes only if it actually wants the stock. It feels=
 no sense of obligation. It is not in the business of trading with you.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bank has other people=E2=80=99s p=
hone numbers. If you want to sell a bunch of stock or bonds all at once, th=
e bank will be able to turn around and sell it to other investors. The bank=
 is in the business of distribution, of intermediating trades, of finding b=
uyers for sellers and sellers for buyers. The bank will know who wants your=
 stock, and so it will be in a good position to quote you a price.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bank has money. If you don=E2=80=99t w=
ant to wait around for the bank to call a bunch of potential buyers, that=
=E2=80=99s fine; the bank can just buy your stock for its own account, give=
 you the money now, and then try to resell it to all of its other customers=
 over however long that takes. The bank intermediates trades in time; it ta=
kes risk on its balance sheet because it knows who to call.</li></ol><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditionally these things go together. If the bank =
knows who=E2=80=99s buying and=C2=A0who=E2=80=99s selling, it is profitable=
 for the bank to be in the middle, selling to the buyers and buying from th=
e sellers for its own account and collecting the spread between them. (And =
vice versa: If you are in the business of making markets, buying stuff in t=
he hopes of quickly flipping it at a profit, it is good to be in touch with=
 lots of buyers and sellers.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the=
y are not=C2=A0<em>necessarily=C2=A0</em>connected. You could in theory hav=
e a business where you talk to a lot of buyers and sellers, and try to matc=
h them up with each other, but you never actually put any of your own money=
 at risk buying from the sellers or selling to the buyers. (This is, for in=
stance, how most banks=E2=80=99 mergers-and-acquisitions businesses work.[1=
])</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the stereotype is that, since the 20=
08 financial crisis, banks have become more risk-averse with their own mone=
y, and regulators have limited their ability to commit money to trading. We=
 have talked about this from time to time in the bond market: =E2=80=9CPeop=
le are worried about bond market liquidity,=E2=80=9D I used to say a lot, b=
ecause banks had stereotypically cut back on buying and selling bonds for t=
heir own accounts.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a good <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27100902.294602/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTgvdGhlLTViLWhlZGdl=
LWZ1bmQtc3Rhci1lbnRhbmdsZWQtaW4tdS1zLXMtbW9yZ2FuLXN0YW5sZXktcHJvYmU_Y21waWQ=
9QkJEMDMyMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZX=
R0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB8f1b0073" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> Bloomberg News story</a> about this phenomenon =
but in stocks. If you have a small amount of stock to sell, you do that ele=
ctronically. But=C2=A0if you have a lot of stock to sell, you call a bank, =
because you have the bank=E2=80=99s phone number. Then the bank calls Frank=
 Fu, because the bank has his phone number, and he has the money:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When Frank Fu, a Cornell-educated engine=
er, opened his own hedge fund two years ago, he picked an unlikely niche fo=
r an introvert.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">His CaaS Capital Management=
 would focus on block trading, one of the last bastions of old Wall Street,=
 where big slugs of stock are sold through person-to-person negotiation, ev=
en cajoling, rather than electronic venues. Many practitioners are bro-y --=
 the type who played college football. For Friday happy hours, Fu=E2=80=99s=
 colleagues unzip their CaaS puffer vests and break out chess boards in a c=
onference room.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yet Fu, 39, soon managed to=
 establish close ties with investment banks including Morgan Stanley, the j=
uggernaut of the equities world. His pitch: CaaS would =E2=80=9Cpartner=E2=
=80=9D with them, positioning itself for preferential treatment. Prospectiv=
e investors say CaaS has boasted to them of quickly becoming one of the big=
gest U.S. funds dedicated to block trading, getting a first look at deals a=
nd gaining entry to virtually every IPO in the country. In the firm=E2=80=
=99s first full year Fu posted a jaw-dropping 76% return. ...</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While a coterie of firms has said they, too, help bank=
s with block trades, none has been more effusive than CaaS in making that i=
ts raison d=E2=80=99etre. Its name is an acronym for =E2=80=9CCapital as a =
Service.=E2=80=9D The firm had just over $650 million in assets under manag=
ement at the end of February, but it=E2=80=99s been able to leverage that u=
p, wielding somewhere around $5 billion in firepower so it=E2=80=99s able t=
o pounce if banks need to unload stock. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Fu typically agrees to participate in about half the blocks he=E2=80=
=99s offered, making the decision based on the discount, his portfolio=E2=
=80=99s other holdings and computer models, CaaS told prospective investors=
. The firm typically carries about 200 blocks at a time, waiting anywhere f=
rom two days to five months, or longer, to unload them after purchase. As a=
 good trading partner, Fu expects banks to send shares from hot IPOs his wa=
y.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The context here is t=
hat regulators have been probing the block-trading business to see if anyth=
ing nefarious is happening (mainly: banks maybe leaking block trades to hed=
ge funds which then short the stock), and Fu is =E2=80=9Csaid to be among m=
ore than a dozen industry executives whose communications are being scrutin=
ized.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But note that this is sort o=
f a post-crisis business, the business of=C2=A0<em>providing liquidity to b=
anks</em>. It used to be that the banks provided the liquidity! (They still=
 do, in the sense that they give Fu leverage! But that=E2=80=99s different.=
)=C2=A0It used to be that if you wanted someone to buy stock at a discount =
and work out of it over a few days or longer, the investment bank would jus=
t do that. =E2=80=9CCapital as a service=E2=80=9D would have been a reasona=
ble description of a big investment bank. Now that is a service that someon=
e provides <em>to=C2=A0</em>the banks, that the banks have to outsource. An=
d if you provide it you can make 76% returns.</p><table class=3D"liveintent=
-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center"=
>
