<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Nickel</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last Thursday=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27100902.294602/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTcvbmlja2VsLWNhbi10LWZpbmQt=
YS1wcmljZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIxMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9=
zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAzMjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1Zm=
Y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9d80c8ae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">I proposed</a> a simple model =
for nickel prices on the London Metal Exchange:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-=
type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Nickel is worth some amount of money, say $30,000 per ton.[2]=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For reasons of historical oopsies=
, nickel trading on the LME was suspended for a week, and reopened on Wedne=
sday at a price of $48,078.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">LME li=
mited, in advance,=C2=A0how much the nickel price could drop each day. The =
limit was 5% last Wednesday, and it=C2=A0increased to 8% on Thursday.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Each of these drops would bring the LM=
E nickel price to a number that was=C2=A0<em>still much higher than $30,000=
</em>, which is what nickel is worth.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">Why would you pay more for nickel than it is worth?</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">So nickel would open for trading each day, drop by wh=
atever the limit was, and close again. Some token amount of trading would g=
et done in order to move the price down, but not much, since the prices kep=
t being too high and could not fall to their natural level.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Eventually the prices will fall to the correct le=
vel and there will be trading again; I estimated this would happen roughly =
this Tuesday.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Isn=E2=80=99t this d=
umb?</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This model held up pretty well? =
Nickel fell 8% on Thursday, the daily limit, on virtually no trading. Then =
the LME increased the limit to 12% on Friday, and nickel fell by 12%, on vi=
rtually no trading. For today=E2=80=99s session, the LME <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27100902.294602/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubG1l=
LmNvbS9hcGkvc2l0ZWNvcmUvTWVtYmVyTm90aWNlc1NlYXJjaEFwaS9Eb3dubG9hZD9pZD0yMzE=
1Nzc5Zi1kZDA0LTQ2NTItOTg3MC04N2M0YTZiNTFiYzM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6c310=
293" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">increased the limit to 15%</a>, and nickel promptly traded dow=
n 15%, for some reason causing the LME to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/27100902.294602/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubG1lLmNvbS9hcGkvc2l=
0ZWNvcmUvTWVtYmVyTm90aWNlc1NlYXJjaEFwaS9Eb3dubG9hZD9pZD03N2M5Yzc0OC0wYjliLT=
Q4ZTAtOTlhOC02YmQ2ZjU5ODI1YWY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCba5b906a" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
cancel some more trades</a>. The price is still wrong, but it is within sho=
uting distance of the right price. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27100902.294602/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMjEvbG1lLW5pY2tlbC1kcm9wcy1ieS0xNS1saW=
1pdC1uYXJyb3dpbmctZ2FwLXdpdGgtc2hhbmdoYWktcHJpY2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMTIyX01PT=
kVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09=
MjIwMzIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcd82c1a2"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> Bloomberg News</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">N=
ickel fell by the daily limit for a fourth straight session on the London M=
etal Exchange as prices continue to nosedive after spiking earlier this mon=
th in an unprecedented short squeeze.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Futur=
es fell by 15% to $31,380 a ton. in the biggest drop since 2015. That=E2=80=
=99s within reach of prices on the Shanghai Futures Exchange, and close to =
the $30,000 level that some traders have said would draw in buyers and allo=
w the nickel market to start trading again in earnest. =E2=80=A6</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf we do not get a market to trade on, how w=
ill people move positions?=E2=80=9D Malcolm Freeman, a director at Kingdom =
Futures, said in an emailed note. =E2=80=9CWith much of the trade standing =
aside and many fund managers exiting the metals, it is becoming hard to see=
 where liquidity will come from in the short term.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">While the market reopened on Wednesday, trading remained e=
ssentially frozen last week as the daily limits stopped prices from falling=
 to a level where buyers were willing to bid. There were 103 lots of nickel=
, or 618 tons, traded by 8:02 on the LME on Monday.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The market is still effectively closed, but it =
is ticking closer to being open. This Tuesday =E2=80=94=C2=A0tomorrow =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0still seems like a good guess for when nickel will be back.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27100902.294602/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTgvZ29sZG1hbi1iaWRzLWZvci1uaWNrZWwtb2ZmL=
WV4Y2hhbmdlLWFib3V0LTMyLWJlbG93LWxtZS1wcmljZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIxMjJfTU9ORVlT=
VFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA=
zMjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5f74b0ab" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> another Bloomberg News story</a> from last Friday:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman Sachs Group Inc. traders have been offeri=
ng to trade nickel away from the London Metal Exchange, according to people=
 familiar with the matter, at prices that imply a further sharp drop in pri=
ces.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank has been offering to trade co=
ntracts in commodity index products, such as the S&amp;P GSCI, whose consti=
tuents include nickel, the people said, implying a bid and offer for the ni=
ckel price. The bank=E2=80=99s proposals imply a bid for nickel at about $2=
5,000 a ton, and an offer about $37,000 a ton, the people said, asking not =
to be named as the matter isn=E2=80=99t public. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">The mid-point of Goldman=E2=80=99s bid and offer, $31,000 a =
ton, is roughly where some traders expect the market to unfreeze, Bloomberg=
 reported earlier.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If yo=
u are in the business of trading commodity index products, and nickel is in=
 your index, and trading in nickel is either frozen (as it was until last W=
ednesday) or semi-frozen=C2=A0and at obviously wrong prices (as it was star=
ting last Thursday), how do you set a price for your commodity index? The b=
asic answer is that you=C2=A0use your best guess at the correct nickel pric=
e ($30,000-ish), and, since you might be wrong and can=E2=80=99t hedge your=
 nickel exposure, you widen the bid-ask spread to compensate you for the ri=
sk.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It helps if the index is mostly <em>not=
=C2=A0</em>nickel, though. Nickel represents <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/27100902.294602/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3BnbG9iYWwuY29t=
