om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Vanguard taxes</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Generally the way U.S. tax law works i=
s that if you buy stocks and they go up, you don=E2=80=99t have to pay any =
taxes until you sell. When you sell, you have to pay capital gains taxes.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are some exceptions.=C2=A0One exceptio=
n is that if you buy stocks in your 401(k) tax-advantaged retirement accoun=
t, and you sell them to buy other stocks in the 401(k), you <em>don=E2=80=
=99t</em> pay taxes; a 401(k) defers taxes until you take money out at reti=
rement.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another exception is that if =
you buy shares in a mutual fund, and they go up, and you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0</em>sell, you might have to pay taxes anyway. A mutual fund pool=
s your money with many other people=E2=80=99s money and buys a bunch of sto=
cks for all of you. And if the mutual fund sells stocks, it incurs capital =
gains taxes, which it passes on to its holders. Roughly speaking what this =
means is that if you invest in a mutual fund, and it goes up, and you=C2=A0=
<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>sell, but=C2=A0<em>other</em> investors in the =
mutual fund <em>do=C2=A0</em>sell, then <em>you</em> have to pay taxes. (As=
 do they.) One reason people like to invest in exchange-traded funds is tha=
t this rule is weird and the ETF business has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/27100902.294602/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS9=
zZWFyY2g_cT1tYXR0K2xldmluZStldGYraGVhcnRiZWF0JnJsej0xQzVDSEZBX2VuVVM4MDdVUz=
gwNyZvcT1tYXR0K2xldmluZStldGYraGVhcnRiZWF0JmFxcz1jaHJvbWUuMC42OWk1OS4zNTg5a=
jBqNyZzb3VyY2VpZD1jaHJvbWUmaWU9VVRGLTg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB719907e7" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">found ways to avoid it</a>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ge=
nerally speaking this is a small constant drag: You invest in a mutual fund=
 with lots of other people, and every year some of them withdraw their mone=
y (to pay for retirement or to buy different mutual funds or whatever), and=
 you have to pay some taxes on some of your gains. But if you invest in a m=
utual fund with 1,000 other people, and they all decide to withdraw from th=
e mutual fund at the same time, then the mutual fund will have to sell almo=
st all of its stocks, which means that you will have to pay taxes on almost=
 all of your unrealized gains in the fund all at once, and you will be anno=
yed.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a weird=C2=A0<a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27100902.294602/aHR0cHM6Ly9h=
c3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JoVHpackFGWHl5QS9=
2MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe66c93a0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">lawsuit against the Vanguard=
 Group</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Vanguard offers =E2=
=80=9Cset-it-and-forget-it=E2=80=9D target date retirement funds. These fun=
ds are organized as a trust and managed by the same trustees. The investmen=
t strategy is based on a target retirement year, such as 2030 or 2050. Vang=
uard offers two tiers of target date funds: (1) funds for individuals and r=
etirement plans with less than $100M (the =E2=80=9CRetail Funds=E2=80=9D); =
and (2) funds for retirement plans with over $100M (the =E2=80=9CInstitutio=
nal Funds=E2=80=9D). The strategy and investments are the same, but the Ins=
titutional Funds charge lower management fees. =E2=80=A6.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Normally, target date funds don=E2=80=99t sell many assets, =
so capital gains distributions are minimal. But beginning in December of 20=
20, Vanguard itself caused an =E2=80=9Celephant stampede=E2=80=9D sell off =
from its Retail Funds. Vanguard chose to open its Institutional Funds (whic=
h=C2=A0hold the same assets as the Retail Funds) to all retirement plans wi=
th at least $5M, so that retirement plans invested in the Retail Funds coul=
d sell their shares and move over to cheaper, but otherwise identical, Inst=
itutional Funds. And this is what happened.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>To raise cash to redeem so many shares, the Retail Funds were forced to se=
ll off as much as 15% of their assets (or even more). When these assets wer=
e sold, the Retail Funds recognized capital gains on the assets. The result=
ing capital gains distributions to investors were unprecedented (40 times p=
revious levels). While this didn=E2=80=99t hurt retirement plans, it left t=
axable investors holding the tax bag.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Vanguard had other, readily-available ways to lower costs for retirement p=
lans without hurting its taxable investors. But it either did not even cons=
ider these options, or did not care about hurting its smaller, taxable inve=
stors. This was a gross violation of Vanguard=E2=80=99s fiduciary duties (a=
mong other legal duties).</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Much=
 of the money in this fund was in corporate 401(k)s, which don=E2=80=99t ca=
re about incurring taxes. Some of it was in individual taxable accounts, wh=
ich do care, and which did incur taxes when the corporate 401(k)s sold.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is that a reason to sue Vanguard? I don=E2=80=
=99t know. The maximal reading of this lawsuit is that a mutual fund has a =
fiduciary duty to its investors to minimize their taxes, and that if it=C2=
=A0does something that causes people to withdraw their money =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if it raises fees or has a bad run of investing or a manager retires or =
it introduces a different, better mutual fund =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that is a=
 violation of that duty. That seems a bit strong.</p><table class=3D"header=
" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
